<div xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml"><p>Bad times are perfect opportunities to test media and try the wacky ideas that have been percolating within your organization. The economy is in free fall. The shift to digital media has begun but hasn&#39;t been fully realized even as print and other traditional media are suffering mightily. Enter the former high priestess of the dot-com bubble, <a href="http://www.slideshare.com/hblodget/mary-meeker-web-20-presentation-presentation?type=powerpoint">Morgan Stanley&#39;s Mary Meeker, with&#0160;her insights into Internet Trends.</a></p>
<p>Social networks, Voice over IP (VoIP) and web video are the rage attracting large audiences and provoking considerable pass-along. Think <a href="http://www.youtube.com">YouTube,</a> <a href="http://www.facebook.com">Facebook,</a> <a href="http://www.skype.com">Skype </a>and <a href="http://www.paypal.com">PalPal.</a>But these drivers of user growth are not necessarily ad friendly either from the perspective of site functionality or from the perspective of audience sensibility. In banker&#39;s terms they are under-monetized because nobody has yet figured out how to get commercial messages embedded in ways that last longer than 15 seconds and that are engaging enough to overcome a hair-trigger sensibility about SPAM and unwanted online ads. Because users think of these sites and others as personal utilities which encorage customization and opt-ins, they expect them to be free of anything <strong><em>they </em></strong>haven&#39;t asked for or specifically chosen. As a result the costs to experiment with these media are relatively cheap and the low CPMs make them atrtractive to brands looking to stick their toes in the online pond.</p>
<p>What Mary doesn&#39;t say is that we have both a credibility and a creative problem. On one hand netziens are rebelling against the gross commercialization of the sites they like the best. They aren&#39;t watching pre-rolls and they want their web video&#0160; free of intrusive ads. For the most part&#0160; TV ads translated to the web and the web-centric video ads have the usual track record for advertising -- most are&#0160;misses and few are hits in terms of popular resonance and pass-along buzz. </p>
<p>When you get past the sites driving usage and interaction and go back to the thousands of sites now represented by the hundreds of ad networks, we have an inventory glut of legendary proportions where low CPMs are matched by even lower credibility and lower creative expectations, From a branding or a direct response perspective banners in most shapes and sizes, with and without rich media applications, suck. Add to this general belief serious doubts about click fraud, parity among networks and large numbers of advertisers who have spent big money for little return and you have a buyers market with huge opportunities to pick up and test affordable campaigns, assuming you can create messages that are compelling.</p>
<p>Its also time to test re-marketing and behavioral targeting, both use nominally sophisticated techniques to follow people and serve them up messages based on directly expressed&#0160;or inferred interests.. The trick is to negotiate low prices and to guess right in terms of the messages and offers&#0160;served up. For many of my clients these experiments have had the most interesting runs and have returned&#0160;the greatest ROI in the shortest time periods.</p>
<p>For some unexplainable reason many new start-ups and services expect advertisers to make good on their business plans, even in a global recession. There will be all kinds of mobile Internet, 3G devices and place-based media joining the fray for the shrinking pot of ad dollars. Many of these will be interesting, but unproven ideas, and if money remains tight you&#39;ll have a chance to play with them on the cheap. Though look to prove conceptual validity rather than&#0160;strong branding results or significant leads and direct sales.</p>
<p>Miss Mary says &quot;value&quot; is the key to growth and survival. Offer advertisers much more for their money and offer consumers and web surfers deals when and where they want them.&#0160;Bad times spell opportunity to break out of existing patterns, test-and-learn new tactics and gain awareness or market share by leveraging low negotiable prices. Its a time to go for it not to run away from it.</p>
<p>&#0160;&#0160;</p></div>
